SIMPLE: reeding
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reeding
<hw>Reed"ing</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧d"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
4th <er>Reed</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A small
convex molding; a reed (see <xex>Illust.</xex> <sd>(i)</sd> of
<er>Molding</er>); one of several set close together to decorate a
surface; also, decoration by means of reedings; -- the reverse of
<contr>fluting</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Several <ex>reedings</ex> are often placed together,
parallel to each other, either projecting from, or inserted into, the
adjoining surface. The decoration so produced is then called, in
general, <ex>reeding</ex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The nurling on the edge of a coin; -- commonly
called <xex>milling</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reedless</ent>⟦br⟧
